{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17652176","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17652176"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:33:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:33:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18516"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18516","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18516"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0,0.7,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11245"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78532"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11245","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11245"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18516"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63873"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7425"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26068"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26280"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26908"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78532","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78532"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe acetabulum is a cup-shaped socket on the lateral aspect of the hip bone that articulates with the head of the femur to form the hip joint. A number of bones join to form the acetabulum.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following are these bones?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ilium and ischium only","Ilium and pubis only","Ilium, ischium and pubis","Sacrum, ilium and ischium","Ischium and pubis only"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe acetabulum is formed by the fusion of three bones: \u003Cstrong\u003Eilium, ischium and pubis (image)\u003C/strong\u003E. Each bone contributes approximately one-third of the acetabulum. The ilium forms the superior portion, the ischium forms the posteroinferior portion, and the pubis forms the anteroinferior portion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIlium and ischium only\u003C/strong\u003E - This omits the pubic contribution to the anteroinferior acetabulum\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIlium and pubis only\u003C/strong\u003E - This omits the ischial contribution to the posteroinferior acetabulum\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESacrum, ilium and ischium\u003C/strong\u003E - The sacrum does not contribute to the acetabulum\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIschium and pubis only\u003C/strong\u003E - This omits the ilial contribution to the superior acetabulum\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese three bones fuse during development to form a single hip bone (os coxae). The Y-shaped fusion line between them can be seen in the acetabulum of developing bones.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The acetabulum is formed by fusion of three bones: ilium, ischium and pubis","The ilium contributes to the superior portion of the acetabulum","The ischium forms the posteroinferior portion of the acetabulum while the pubis forms the anteroinferior portion"],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cAcetabulum 03 anterior view\u201d by DBCLS\u00a0is licensed under\u00a0Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 2.1 jp Unported license. (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.1/jp/deed.en). \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Acetabulum_03_anterior_view.png\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63873"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18516"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21403"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21403"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/reCtRzF7avtbjsWNZbQtfKhyEzBFUD.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/reCtRzF7avtbjsWNZbQtfKhyEzBFUD.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":640}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63873","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63873"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T11:27:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T11:28:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11245"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78532"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null